Neil Leifer on WordPress";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:21:"http://ma.tt/?p=42116";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:46:"http://ma.tt/2013/01/neil-leifer-on-wordpress/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3430:"<p>One of my favorite photographers, <a href="http://neilleifer.com/">Neil Leifer, has a beautiful new WordPress.com-powered site</a>. For the past few years I&#8217;ve had this photo in my office:</p>\n<p><a href="http://s.ma.tt/files/2013/01/ali-williams.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-42117" alt="Ali - Williams (Overhead)" src="http://i2.wp.com/s.ma.tt/files/2013/01/ali-williams.jpg?resize=640%2C648" /></a></p>\n<p>The story behind it is pretty interesting, taken from <a href="http://bermangraphics.com/press/leifer.htm">this interview with Larry Berman and Chris Maher</a>:</p>\n<div class="blockquote">\n<blockquote><b>Chris/Larry:</b>It&#8217;s actually quite a different question to say what are your favorites verses what do you feel are your best photographs.</p>\n<p><b>Neil:</b>I know, and my best picture ever, in my opinion, is my Ali Cleveland Williams picture that I shot from overhead. I dont usually hang my own photos, I collect other peoples pictures. But that pictures been hanging in my living room as long as I can remember. I have a 40&#215;40 print of it which is hung in a diamond shape with Williams at the top. That&#8217;s the guy thats on the canvas on his back.</p>\n<p><b>Chris/Larry:</b> Its remarkably abstract for a sports picture.</p>\n<p><b>Neil:</b>I think its the only picture in my career that theres nothing I would do different with it. You look at pictures and think that you can always improve them no matter how successful the shoot is. Part of what motivates you to go on to the next shoot is every once in a while you get a picture, whether it&#8217;s the cover of the magazine or an inside spread, that&#8217;s as good as you think you could have made it. And then a week later you see a couple of things that you could improve slightly. A month later you might see a few more things. It doesnt diminish the quality of that picture. It simply means that there&#8217;s always room for improvement.</p>\n<p><b>Chris/Larry:</b>Youre learning for the future?</p>\n<p><b>Neil:</b>Exactly. Its sort of what motivates you to go on. If I were to do the Cleveland Williams Ali picture again, I would do it exactly the same. And more important is that no one will ever do it better because it cant be done like that anymore. Today the ring is different and the fighters dress in multi colored outfits like wrestlers. Back then the champ wore white and the challenger wore black. Today, when you look down at the ring from above, you see the Budweiser Beer logo in the center and around it is the network logo thats televising the fight. Whether its Showtime or HBO, they have their logo two or three times on the canvas. The logo of promoter of the fight, Don King Presents, is also visible. That&#8217;s why that picture couldn&#8217;t be taken today. So not only did the picture work out better than any Ive ever taken, but its one thatll never be taken again.</p>\n<p><img alt="Neil Leifer" src="http://i0.wp.com/bermangraphics.com/images/Neil-Ali_Williams-p143.jpg?resize=300%2C265" border="0" /></p>\n<p><b>Chris/Larry:</b>Where are you in this picture?</p>\n<p><b>Neil:</b>Im at 11:00 oclock, as I remember it. Im in a blue shirt leaning on the canvas with a camera in each hand.</p></blockquote>\n</div>\n<p>It&#8217;s always an honor to have a great creator make their home on the web with WordPress.</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Tue, 29 Jan 2013 11:22:37 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4:"Matt";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:26;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:13:"\n	\n	\n	\n	\n	\n	\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:2:{s:0:"";a:5:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:27:"bbPress: bbPress 2.3 Beta 1";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:28:"http://bbpress.org/?p=125680";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:51:"http://bbpress.org/blog/2013/01/bbpress-2-3-beta-1/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1186:"<p>Today we tagged bbPress 2.3 beta 1 in the WordPress.org plugin repository. This means we think 2.3 ready to release into the wild, but want to get a few extra eyes on things first. It represents the 4th major iteration of bbPress as a plugin for your self-hosted WordPress powered website, and we&#8217;re excited about how far we&#8217;ve come.</p>\n<p>Even though bbPress 2.3 is developer tested, we dont recommend you run it on a production site quite yet. Instead, set up a test site or a local installation to play with. If you find a bug, patch it or let us know.</p>\n<p>We are aiming to release bbPress 2.3 in the first week of February. Now&#8217;s the time to<a href="http://codex.wordpress.org/Reporting_Bugs">report some feedback</a>!</p>\n<p>If you think you found a bug, please report it on the<a href="http://bbpress.trac.wordpress.org">bbPress Core Trac</a>. If you find a security vulnerability, please be discrete and let us know privately using one of the methods posted on the<a href="http://wordpress.org/about/contact/">WordPress contact page</a>.</p>\n<p><a href="http://downloads.wordpress.org/plugin/bbpress.zip">Download bbPress 2.3, Beta 1 </a></p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Mon, 28 Jan 2013 20:18:38 plugins</h3>\n<p><a href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/cross-promotion-content-recommendations/"><strong>Cross-Promotion Content Recommendations</strong></a> drives a fresh new audience to your site by cross-promoting your posts with other related bloggers.</p>\n<p><a href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/upload-photo-to-facebook/"><strong>Upload Photo to Facebook</strong></a> uploads photos to your Facebook profile.</p>\n<h3>Updated plugins</h3>\n<p><a href="http://calendarscripts.info/autoresponder-wordpress.html"><strong>BFT Autoresponder</strong></a> allows scheduling of automated autoresponder messages and managing a mailing list.</p>\n<p><a href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/hyperdb/"><strong>HyperDB</strong></a> is an advanced database class that supports replication, failover, load balancing, and partitioning.</p>\n<p><a href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/wpmarketplace/"><strong>WP Marketplace</strong></a> is a full-featured shopping cart/e-commerce system that is extremely easy to install and even easier to maintain.</p>\n<img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/weblogtoolscollection/UXMP/~4/S8WZArn7jUk" height="1" width="1" />";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Mon, 28 Jan 2013 14:00:55 src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/weblogtoolscollection/UXMP/~4/khedzDlh4gk" height="1" width="1" />";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Sat, 26 Jan 2013 14:00:03 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"James";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:29;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:13:"\n	\n	\n	\n	\n	\n	\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:2:{s:0:"";a:5:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:44:"Mike Little: WordPress  A 10 year journey";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:35:"http://zed1.com/journalized/?p=1867";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:147:"http://zed1.com/journalized/archives/2013/01/25/wordpress-a-10-year-journey/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=wordpress-a-10-year-journey";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2500:"<p><a href="http://zed1.com/journalized/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/wordpress-logo-notext-rgb.png"><img class="size-thumbnail wp-image-1873 alignleft" alt="WordPress logo" src="http://zed1.com/journalized/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/wordpress-logo-notext-rgb-150x150.png" width="150" height="150" /></a></p>\n<p>I find it hard to believe but it has now been <strong>ten years</strong> since my fateful <a href="http://ma.tt/2003/01/the-blogging-software-dilemma/#comment-445">comment on Matt&#8217;s blog </a>that kicked off what became the <a href="http://wordpress.org/">WordPress</a> project!<br />\nFrom those humble beginnings of a simple unmaintained blogging platform (b2/Cafelog) to a world-beating open source CMS. B2/Cafelog wasused by perhaps 2,000 bloggers. Now WordPress runs more than <a href="http://en.wordpress.com/stats/">60 million sites</a> around the world. That&#8217;s over <a href="http://w3techs.com/technologies/overview/content_management/all">17.5% of the web</a>!</p>\n<h2>WordPress Industry</h2>\n<p>WordPress now supports a world-wide industry from individual <a href="http://mikelittle.org/">WordPress specialists</a> like me (I&#8217;ve just completed my fourth year as my own company <a href="http://zed1.com/">zed1.com</a>); small WordPress-based companies like <a href="http://codeforthepeople.com/">Code for the People</a>;through to multi-million dollar companies like <a href="http://www.copyblogger.com/">Copyblogger</a>, <a href="http://www.woothemes.com/">WooThemes</a>, and of course <a href="http://automattic.com/">Automattic</a>.</p>\n<p>Praise must go as usual to the <a href="http://make.wordpress.org/">fantastic community</a> around WordPress, the singular vision of <a href="http://ma.tt/">Matt Mullenweg</a>, and the awesome power of the <a title="GNU General Public License" href="http://www.gnu.org/licenses/gpl.html">GNU GPL</a> open source license.</p>\n<h2>Here&#8217;s to the next year</h2>\n<p>As WordPress enters it&#8217;s <strong>eleventh</strong> year, with version 3.5.1 recently released and <a href="http://make.wordpress.org/core/">version 3.6 currently in the making</a>, I predict it will be another great year for <a title="Personal Publishing Platform" href="http://wordpress.org">WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a href="http://zed1.com/journalized/archives/2013/01/25/wordpress-a-10-year-journey/">WordPress &#8211; A 10 year journey</a> appeared first on <a href="http://zed1.com/journalized">Mike Little&#039;s Journalized</a>.</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Fri, 25 Jan 2013 10:49:04 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:11:"Mike Little";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:30;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:13:"\n	\n	\n	\n	\n	\n	\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:2:{s:0:"";a:5:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:49:"Weblog Tools Collection: WordPress 3.5.1 Released";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:41:"http://weblogtoolscollection.com/?p=12577";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:73:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/weblogtoolscollection/UXMP/~3/UVRBgAFV70k/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1397:"<p><a href="http://wordpress.org">WordPress</a> 3.5.1 <a href="http://wordpress.org/news/2013/01/wordpress-3-5-1/">has been released</a>. This is both a security and maintenance release, fixing <a href="http://core.trac.wordpress.org/query?milestone=3.5.1">37 bugs</a>.</p>\n<p>In particular, this release fixes a bug which could cause HTML elements to be unexpectedly removed by the Editor, fixes a bug which caused HTML elements to be unexpectedly removed from scheduled posts, provides workarounds for certain misconfigurations which could prevent JavaScript from loading in the Dashboard, and fixes three cross-site scripting vulnerabilities and one server-side request forgery vulnerability.</p>\n<p>If you have trouble automatically updating to WordPress 3.5.1, you may be on an IIS server and will need to follow <a href="http://codex.wordpress.org/Version_3.5.1#Windows_Servers_Running_IIS">these instructions</a>.</p>\n<p>This is a security release, so it is recommended for all users. If you run into trouble with WordPress 3.5.1, stop by <a href="http://wordpress.org/support/topic/troubleshooting-wordpress-35-master-list">the master list of known issues</a> and post to <a href="http://wordpress.org/support/">the support forums</a> if your problem isn&#8217;t covered there.</p>\n<img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/weblogtoolscollection/UXMP/~4/UVRBgAFV70k" height="1" width="1" />";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Fri, 25 Jan 2013 04:15:08 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"James";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:31;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:13:"\n	\n	\n	\n	\n	\n	\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:2:{s:0:"";a:5:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:58:"Dev Blog: WordPress 3.5.1 Maintenance and Security Release";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:33:"http://wordpress.org/news/?p=2531";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:50:"http://wordpress.org/news/2013/01/wordpress-3-5-1/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2494:"<p>WordPress 3.5.1 is now available. Version 3.5.1 is the first maintenance release of 3.5, <a href="http://core.trac.wordpress.org/milestone/3.5.1">fixing 37 bugs</a>. It is also a security release for all previous WordPress versions. For a full list of changes, consult the <a href="http://core.trac.wordpress.org/query?milestone=3.5.1">list of tickets</a>and the<a href="http://core.trac.wordpress.org/log/branches/3.5?rev=23341&stop_rev=23167">changelog</a>, which include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Editor: Prevent certain HTML elements from being unexpectedly removed or modified in rare cases.</li>\n<li>Media: Fix a collection of minor workflow and compatibility issues in the new media manager.</li>\n<li>Networks: Suggest proper rewrite rules when creating a new network.</li>\n<li>Prevent scheduled posts from being stripped of certain HTML, such as video embeds, when they are published.</li>\n<li>Work around some misconfigurations that may have caused some JavaScript in the WordPress admin area to fail.</li>\n<li>Suppress some warnings that could occur when a plugin misused the database or user APIs.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Additionally, a bug affecting Windows servers running IIS can prevent updating from 3.5 to 3.5.1. If you receive the error &#8220;Destination directory for file streaming does not exist or is not writable,&#8221; you will need to <a href="http://codex.wordpress.org/Version_3.5.1">follow the steps outlined on the Codex</a>.</p>\n<p>WordPress 3.5.1 also addresses the following security issues:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>A server-side request forgeryvulnerabilityand remote port scanning using pingbacks. This vulnerability, which could potentially be used to expose information and compromise a site, affects all previous WordPress versions. This was fixed by the WordPress security team. We&#8217;d like to thank security researchers <a href="http://codeseekah.com/">Gennady Kovshenin</a> and <a href="http://www.ethicalhack3r.co.uk/">Ryan Dewhurst</a> for reviewing our work.</li>\n<li>Two instances of cross-site scripting via shortcodes and post content. These issues were discovered by Jon Cave of the WordPress security team.</li>\n<li>A cross-site scripting vulnerability in the external library Plupload. Thanks to the Moxiecode team for working with us on this, and for releasing Plupload 1.5.5 to address this issue.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong><a href="http://wordpress.org/download/">Download 3.5.1</a>or visit Dashboard  Updates in your site admin to update now.</strong></p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Thu, 24 Jan 2013 22:23:03 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:12:"Andrew Nacin";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:32;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:13:"\n	\n	\n	\n	\n	\n	\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:2:{s:0:"";a:5:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:61:"BuddyPress: BuddyPress 1.6.4 Maintenance and Security Release";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"http://buddypress.org/?p=151669";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:80:"http://buddypress.org/2013/01/buddypress-1-6-4-maintenance-and-security-release/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:615:"<p><a href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/buddypress/">BuddyPress 1.6.4</a> (now available for download) is a maintenance and security release, and a safe and easy update for all previous BuddyPress versions.</p>\n<p>Version <a href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/buddypress/">1.6.4</a> includes some security hardening inside the bp-default theme&#8217;s ajax functionality. These issues were responsibly disclosed by Maty Siman.</p>\n<p><strong><a href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/buddypress/">Download 1.6.4</a> now or visit Dashboard  Updates in your site admin to update now.</strong></p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Thu, 24 Jan 2013 22:10:55 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:17:"John James Jacoby";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:33;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:13:"\n	\n	\n	\n	\n	\n	\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:2:{s:0:"";a:5:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:68:"Ping-O-Matic: Engage: Make Your Online Home a Place for Conversation";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:32:"http://blog.pingomatic.com/?p=77";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:49:"http://blog.pingomatic.com/2013/01/24/engagement/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2763:"<p><a href="http://pingomatic.com/">Ping-O-Matic</a>is all aboutgetting your latest content out into the world and driving more traffic to your blog. And if you have a blog, chances are you want to be part of a larger community. You don&#8217;t just want to create and share your stuff &#8212; you want to connect with people who share your interests and passions in a meaningful way.</p>\n<p>Publishing a post is just one step in blogging &#8212; getting people to engage with you is another. How do you start a conversation?</p>\n<h3>Here are some tips:</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>End with a prompt.</strong>At the end of a post, encourage comments by asking a specific question or two, which is a better way of generating feedback than more general &#8220;Leave a comment&#8221; or &#8220;What do you think?&#8221; prompts. Your blog isnt just a monologue &#8212; you want to open up the discussion to others.</li>\n<li><strong>Reply to comments.</strong>Your job doesnt end when you hit publish. When readers leave comments, keep the conversation going with a thoughtful reply.</li>\n<li><strong>But dont reply to every comment.</strong>If you receive many comments and reply to each with a generic one-liner (&#8220;Thanks!&#8221;), your comment thread won&#8217;t be interesting. Feel free to reply to first-time visitors to welcome them to your site, but in general, reply only if you have something substantial to add to the existing conversation.</li>\n<li><strong>Moderate with care.</strong>Its best not to encourage or allow nasty and abusive comments. They intimidate new readers, derail conversations, and distract you from good blogging. It&#8217;s <em>your</em>online home &#8212; don&#8217;t be afraid to give polite warnings to visitors who aren&#8217;t appropriate.</li>\n<li><strong>Post commenting guidelines.</strong>If you find yourself doing a lot of policing, one way to be transparent about the type of comments you will and will not permit is to post simple guidelines. This can help you attract the kind of commenters you want, and deter unwanted behavior.</li>\n<li><strong>Return the visit.</strong>Developing friendships with your readers is one of the best parts of blogging. If you have loyal commenters, make sure you visit and engage on their blogs, too. If they like what you post, chances are youll be into their stuff as well.</li>\n</ul>\n<br />  <a rel="nofollow" href="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/pingomatic.wordpress.com/77/"><img alt="" border="0" src="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/pingomatic.wordpress.com/77/" /></a> <img alt="" border="0" src="http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=blog.pingomatic.com&blog=68432&post=77&subd=pingomatic&ref=&feed=1" width="1" height="1" />";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Thu, 24 Jan 2013 19:22:39 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:11:"Cheri href="https://alexking.org/blog/2013/01/22/15733">Tuesday&#8217;s discussion</a> got me thinking about the differences between Envato&#8217;s marketplace and Apple&#8217;s Mac App Store.</p>\n<p>\n\n.mac-app-store-vs-envato {\n    max-width: 550px;\n    width: 100%;\n}\n.mac-app-store-vs-envato th {\n    border-bottom: 1px solid #999;\n    padding: 5px;\n}\n.mac-app-store-vs-envato tbody td {\n    border: 1px solid #eee;\n    border-left: 0;\n    border-top: 0;\n    padding: 5px;\n    text-align: center;\n    vertical-align: middle;\n}\n.mac-app-store-vs-envato tbody tr:nth-child(odd) td {\n    background-color: #f8f8f8;\n}\n.mac-app-store-vs-envato tbody td:first-child {\n    text-align: left;\n}\n\n</p>\n<table class="mac-app-store-vs-envato" valign="middle">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>&nbsp;</th>\n<th width="30%">Mac App Store</th>\n<th width="30%">Envato</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Developer&#8217;s revenue share</td>\n<td>70%</td>\n<td>33% (or 50-70%<br />if &#8220;exclusive&#8221;)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Also sell your products on your website or other marketplaces?</td>\n<td>Yes</td>\n<td>Yes @ 33%,<br />No @ 50-70%</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Who chooses your software&#8217;s license</td>\n<td>Developer</td>\n<td>Envato</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Who sets the price of your software?</td>\n<td>Developer</td>\n<td>Envato</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>The more I think about it, the more insane I think it is to choose to do business with Envato given their current terms.</p>\n<p>In order to put your products in their marketplace with a semi-reasonable revenue share you are choosing to completely subjugate your business to their whims. You can&#8217;t experiment with your product pricing, you can&#8217;t try other marketplaces, you can&#8217;t sell direct to your customers&#8230; you can&#8217;t even choose your own software license!</p>\n<p>People actually sign up for this?</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Thu, 24 Jan 2013 18:39:59 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4:"Alex";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:36;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:13:"\n	\n	\n	\n	\n	\n	\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:2:{s:0:"";a:5:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:55:"bbPress: bbPress 2.2.4 Maintenance and Security Release";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:28:"http://bbpress.org/?p=125495";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:79:"http://bbpress.org/blog/2013/01/bbpress-2-2-4-maintenance-and-security-release/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:652:"<p><a href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/bbpress/">bbPress 2.2.4</a> (now available for download) is a maintenance and security release, and a safe and easy update for all previous bbPress 2.x versions.</p>\n<p>Version <a href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/bbpress/">2.2.4</a> includes some security hardening inside the Forum Importer/Converter tool, and improves post form output sanitization. Connect";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:30:"http://blog.akismet.com/?p=936";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:80:"http://blog.akismet.com/2013/01/23/sign-into-akismet-with-wordpress-com-connect/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3787:"<p>With the new year upon us, your friends here at <a href="http://automattic.com">Automattic</a>have resolved to make it easier to manage your accounts across all our services.</p>\n<p>Maybe you&#8217;re using <a href="http://akismet.com/">Akismet</a>to stop spam in its tracks, <a href="http://vaultpress.com/">VaultPress</a>to keep your site safe and secure, and <a href="http://polldaddy.com">Polldaddy</a>to find out what your readers are thinking. Maybe you&#8217;re using <a href="http://wordpress.com">WordPress.com</a>to build a fancy new site, or <a href="http://jetpack.me">Jetpack</a>to supercharge your self-hosted one.</p>\n<p>Now you can sign into all these awesome services, including Akismet, with just one account &#8212; your WordPress.com account!</p>\n<h2>Signing into Akismet</h2>\n<p>Starting today, you&#8217;ll be required to sign into Akismet with your WordPress.com account.</p>\n<p>The good news is, if you have an Akismet account, you already have a WordPress.com account! Simply<a href="https://akismet.com/account/">sign into Akismet</a>with the credentials you&#8217;ve been using all along.</p>\n<p><strong>Don&#8217;t have a free WordPress.com account?</strong></p>\n<p>There&#8217;s a good chance you already have one, and don&#8217;t realize it!Try <a href="https://akismet.com/account/">signing into Akismet</a> with the credentials you&#8217;ve been using all along.</p>\n<p>If you really don&#8217;t have a WordPress.com account, it only takes a few seconds to sign up and is totally free! Simply click &#8220;Sign in with WordPress.com&#8221; on the <a href="https://akismet.com/account/">Akismet account page</a>, and then click the &#8220;Need an account?&#8221; link.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-942" alt="signin1" src="http://akismet.files.wordpress.com/2013/01/signin1.jpeg?w=600&h=348" width="600" height="348" /></p>\n<p><strong>Already have a WordPress.com account?</strong></p>\n<p><strong></strong>You&#8217;re all set!Go ahead and <a href="http://akismet.com/account/">sign into Akismet</a> with your fancy WordPress.com account. You might be asked to &#8220;authorize&#8221; Akismet to access your WordPress.com account.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-943" alt="signin2" src="http://akismet.files.wordpress.com/2013/01/signin2.jpeg?w=600&h=231" width="600" height="231" /></p>\n<p><strong>Not sure if you have a WordPress.com account?</strong></p>\n<p>No problem! If you use VaultPress, Polldaddy, Jetpack, IntenseDebate, or Gravatar, you can just sign in with the same account you use for them. Otherwise, just go ahead and try<a href="https://akismet.com/account/">signing into Akismet</a>with the credentials you&#8217;ve been using to sign into Akismet all along.</p>\n<p>If it turns out that you don&#8217;t have a WordPress.com account, you can sign up for a free account in a flash! Simply click &#8220;Sign in with WordPress.com&#8221; on the<a href="https://akismet.com/account/">Akismet account page</a>, and then click the &#8220;Need an account?&#8221; link.We&#8217;ll let you know if we find one that&#8217;s tied to your email address.</p>\n<p><strong>Have any questions?</strong></p>\n<p><a href="http://en.support.wordpress.com/wpcc-faq/">Learn more</a> about how we&#8217;re making it easier to manage all your accounts here at Automattic, or <a href="http://akismet.com/contact/">drop us a line</a>.</p>\n<br />  <a rel="nofollow" Mainly, this meant writing a README (and creating a <a href="https://github.com/alexkingorg/wp-fullscreen-preview-button">proper repo for it on GitHub</a>).</p>\n<p><a href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/fullscreen-preview-button/"><img src="http://alexking.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/fullscreen-editor-preview.png" alt="Fullscreen Editor Preview Button Screenshot" width="562" height="283" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-15744" /></a></p>\n<p>This is a simple one-trick-pony plugin &#8211; it adds a Preview button to the fullscreen editor toolbar. Nothing more, nothing less. If you&#8217;ve been up late at night pining away for this feature, this plugin is your new best friend.</p>\n<p>Enjoy!</p>\n<p>A quick note about support: As this is a free plugin released under the GPL I am offering only &#8220;Product Support&#8221; for this plugin. That means I will do my best to fix bugs and usabiity issues. Contrast this with &#8220;User Support&#8221; which we offer for all of <a href="http://crowdfavorite.com">Crowd Favorite</a>&#8216;s commercial products. This release comes with a slew of features that make it even easier to personalize your calendar, publicize your events, and share what&#8217;s happening around you.</p>\n<p>Unfortunately, with over 20,000 plugins and thousands of themes  not to mention personal customizations  the number of different combinations is practically infinite. It is impossible to test every single variation. New theme and plugin conflicts will inevitably occur with every release. This isn&#8217;t an excuse, but simply a reality of releasing a product in an unstable environment.</p>\n<p>While it can be difficult to reproduce specific bugs, our development team has been working hard to fix the known issues with the calendar. Below is a summary of what we&#8217;ve been working on.</p>\n<p><strong>1.9.1 Pro:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.6em;">Fixed URL issue with calendar page being a subpage of a parent</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.6em;">Fixed URL issue with calendar page sometimes missing trailing slash</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.6em;">Fixed issue with front-end modals not displaying in IE10</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.6em;">Fixed issue with calendar toolbar not updating in shortcode-embedded calendar</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.6em;">Added event venue, organizer, contact, external URL fields to front-end form</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.6em;">Fixed issue with Event Categories not getting saved when submitting an event using the front-end form</span></li>\n</ul>\n<div><strong>1.9.1 Standard:</strong></div>\n<ul>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.6em;">Restored the old front-end Post Your Event button (links to Add New Event screen in WP dashboard)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.6em;">Fixed URL issue with calendar page being a subpage of a parent</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.6em;">Fixed URL issue with calendar page sometimes missing trailing slash</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>In 1.9.2 &#8211; (out now) we have fixed even more issues, including:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.6em;">Fixed Feed issue where events would not be found</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.6em;">Made sure that all our assets (css, javascript, and images) are included without a protocol, making it work better with secure sites</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.6em;">Fixed recurring event feed issue when importing Google Calendars</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.6em;">Added a setting to support a few themes that call the_content() such as Gonzo</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.6em;">Fixed custom time format</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.6em;">Fixed an issue with Permalinks not working on some installations</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p>We are committed to fixing bugs. If you have a reproducible bug, please email us at <a href="mailto://help@time.ly"><em><a class="autohyperlink" href="mailto:help@time.ly" title="mailto:help@time.ly">help@time.ly</a></em></a> and we will add it to our bug tracker. <strong>Please check to see if your bug is a theme or plugin conflict first by changing your theme to TwentyTwelve and seeing if that solves the problem, or disabling your plugins to see which one causes the conflict.</strong></p>\n<p>Thanks for choosing us,<br />\n- The Time.ly Dev &amp; Support Both editions are aimed at connecting regions and interest groups together. However, each is designed for a different type of business or organization.</p>\n<p>Our Standard calendar is for <strong>event creators</strong> &amp;emdash; businesses, bloggers or organizations that want to get the word out in a compelling way about the cool things they&#8217;re doing. The Standard release was primarily focused on bug fixes, but provided some great improvements too, including improved filtering, customization and editing.</p>\n<p>The Pro Calendar is for <strong>event aggregators</strong>. This edition is designed for anyone running a community site, a portal, or a new site or blog, basically hubs for geographic or topic-based communities. The Pro includes all that is offered in the Standard Edition as well as features that will help your website become the best hub possible:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Stream View is a new view that many of you have been asking for.</li>\n<li>Front-end Event Creation allowing your community members to contribute events. This includes editorial tools that keep you in control of what appears on your calendar.</li>\n<li>User Feed Submission. Posting individual events take time, why not ask all the businesses/organizations in your network to download our standard calendar for their website and simply pull in their feed? You can pull it from their site Or they can post the ICS feed on yours.</li>\n<li>Super Widgets. Embed your calendar outside of WordPress and distribute it to other websites (even static HTML sites, and sites hosted on other servers).</li>\n<li>Premium Support.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Thanks again for choosing Timely and being patient while we put out this major release. Rid yourselves of your calendars! The end is nigh! The world will end on December 21st. Were reaching the cataclysm: the 21st ofDecember, 2012 will bring about the end of all things. Maybe. Thats all &#8230; <a href="http://time.ly/the-end-is-nigh-maybe/">Continued</a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Jonathan";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3453:"<p><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-23970" title="Photo: CreativeCommons &gt;Flickr&gt; Some rights reserved by CarlosVanVegas" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/mayancalendarphoto.jpg" alt="Photo: CreativeCommons &gt;Flickr&gt; Some rights reserved by CarlosVanVegas" width="500" height="375" /></p>\n<p>People, throw out your diaries! Rid yourselves of your calendars! The end is nigh! The world will end on December 21st. Were reaching the cataclysm: the 21st ofDecember, 2012 will bring about the end of all things. Maybe.</p>\n<p>Thats all pretty tongue-in-cheek. What happens on the 21st of December 2012 is that we reach the end of one cycle in the old Mayan calendar. People seem to have gotpretty exercised about this, with one poll, as reported by Reuters, showing that 1 in 10 of us are anxious about the world ending on December 21st.</p>\n<p>Of course, there isnt any reason to be worried about this actually happening, as the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maya_calendar" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a> entry on the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maya_calendar" target="_blank">Mayan calandar</a> makes pretty clear. All thats happening isthat were reaching the end of this b&#8217;ak&#8217;tun, and a b&#8217;ak&#8217;tun is nothing more than a way of representing 144,000 days from the act of creation thats supposed to haveoccurred in 3114BC. In the Mayan calendar, the date on what we call the 29th of December is 12.19.19.17.18. The date on the 21st? 13.0.0.0.0!</p>\n<p>Whilst to our eyes this is an unusual way of representing time, theres no reason at all to worry about it. Its a bit like worrying that there will be an apocolypsebecause weve reached the end of a decade, or the end of a century, or the end of a milleniumalthough plenty of people managed to worry about that, too!</p>\n<p>Of course, this is hardly the first time that calendars have caused a stir. In 1752, Great Britain adopted the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gregorian_Calendar" target="_blank">Gregorian Calendar</a>. This required a re-adjustment of dates andso it was that Wednesday 2nd September was followed by Thursday 14th September. Although tales of riots and violence seem to be somewhat overstated, nonetheless itwas certainly an important social and political upheaval.</p>\n<p>So why do we get so vexed about these dates in time if, in fact, theyre actually insignificant? Well, heres one thought. Theres a natural tendency to get spooked bythings that we dont understand. The unknown can be pretty scary sometimes And for all of our advancements in measuring and thinking about time, it still seems to methat the following quote from <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Augustine%27s_Confessions" target="_blank">Augustines Confessions</a> (Book 11, chapter 14) rings true: What, then, is time? If no one asks me, I know what it is. If I wish to explainit to him who asks me, I do not know. Maybejust maybethat sense of mystery that still shrouds the concept of time, coupled to the striking simplicity of some of thenumbers involved (13.0.0.0.0 in the Mayan case, and 2000 in the other Ive talked about) come together to generate a sense of unease. Whatever the explanation forthese unfounded concerns, have a very happy end of this <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B%27ak%27tun" target="_blank">b&#8217;ak&#8217;tun</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:42:"http://time.ly/the-end-is-nigh-maybe/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:3;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:44:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n\n		\n		\n			\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:29:"Life Flashes Before Your Eyes";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:45:"http://time.ly/life-flashes-before-your-eyes/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:54:"http://time.ly/life-flashes-before-your-eyes/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Thu, +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:2:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4:"News";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16:"Thoughts on Time";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:23:"http://time.ly/?p=22749";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:337:"Most of our experiences of events have the same structure. We experience events in time in alinear fashion. These experiences of events, though sometimes a little dull, are perfectly normal. Its that familiar drudgeof one thing after another! But there &#8230; <a href="http://time.ly/life-flashes-before-your-eyes/">Continued</a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Jonathan";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5352:"<p>Most of our experiences of events have the same structure. We experience events in time in alinear fashion. These experiences of events, though sometimes a little dull, are perfectly normal.</p>\n<p>Its that familiar drudgeof one thing after another! But there are some rare experiences that arevery different. These are experiences where all (or at least many) of the events of our lives flashbefore our eyes seemingly all at once. These cases, unlike those that we normally experience,seem to be ones where the regular succession of events is interrupted and we experience wholesections of our past lives in a single instant (or similarly short interval of time).</p>\n<p>In many ways these experiences seem really strange. Not only are these cases where peoplereport re-living events from the past, they are sometimes also associated with a sense of timeslowing down and everything becoming clear. Of course, it seems peculiar to say that time reallyslows down in these cases, or that we really can experience all of those events from our lives.After all, if those events took so many years to occur, how can I possibly experience them in thevery brief time it takes for my life to flash before my eyes?</p>\n<p>Strange as they may be, these experiences are reasonably well documented (as a quick internetsearch reveals!) in a range of different cultures. Whats striking form our own culture is thatthese kinds of experience (of many events flashing before our eyes) are generally supposed to beclosely associated with near death experiences, other features of which include an awareness ofbeing dead, moving through a tunnel and communicating with light.</p>\n<div id="attachment_22753" class="wp-caption alignright" style="width: 310px"><img class="size-medium wp-image-22753" title="MikeBaird" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/MikeBaird1-300x300.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="300" /><p class="wp-caption-text">Photo by Mike Baird, courtesy of Creative Commons</p></div>\n<p>But in fact, in scientific studies, it doesnt seem that there is such a close association. This experience of events where ones life seeming to flash by all at once is sometimes referred to as life review&#8217;and, in one study at least, was only present in 13% of Near Death Experiences.(1) One other interesting feature of near death experiences is that although patients most viewthemselves as being close to death, one study showed that of 58 such patients only 28 were in factin a condition such that, had they not had medical intervention, they would have died.(2)</p>\n<p>Historically, such experiences as having ones life flash before ones eyes have taken on agood deal of religious significance and continue to do so today for some people. Even weresuch experiences to not in fact be caused by any supranatural involvement, this would beunsurprising. Instances of near death experiences frequently lead to people re-examining theirlives and changing the way that they do things.(3)</p>\n<p>Increasingly, though, theres evidence that near death experiences themselves can be explainedwithout recourse to any supranatural being. Indeed, many of the features of near deathexperiences can be triggered simply by stimulating particular regions of the brain.(4) Similarly,there are plausible explanations of the mechanisms by which near death experiences in generalmight be brought about by low CO2 levels in the bloodstream.(5)</p>\n<p>But, be that as it may, there remains a particular fascination with these kinds of experience. Evenif we can ultimately give a scientific explanation for their occurrences, these experiences are sounlike our normal experiences of events in time that they certainly give rise to a sense of wonder.</p>\n<p>I suspect, though, that regardless of any explanation of the cause of these experiences (be thatscientific or otherwise) we would do well to take some advice from a reasonably well-knownquotation that I gather is due to Gerard Way(6): One day your life will flash before your eyes. Makesure it&#8217;s worth watching.</p>\n<p>1 van Lommel, P. van Wees,, R. Meyers,V and Elfferich, I. 2001. Near-death experience insurvivors of cardiac arrest: a prospective study in the Netherlands, Lancet, 358, 2039-45, p. 2041<br />\n2 Owens, J.E., Cook, E.W., Stevenson, I. 1990. Features of &#8220;near-death experience&#8221; in relation towhether or not patients were near death, Lancet, 336, 1175-1177<br />\n3 Again, see the 2001 Lancet piece.<br />\n4 See Mobbs, D. and Watt, C. 2011. There is nothing paranormal about near-death experiences:how neuroscience can explain seeing bright lights, meeting the dead, or being convinced you areone of them, Trends in Cognitive Science, 15, 447-9<br />\n5 <a href="http://ccforum.com/content/14/2/R56" class="autohyperlink" title="http://ccforum.com/content/14/2/R56" target="_blank">ccforum.com/content/14/2/R56</a><br />\n6 <a href="http://www.goodreads.com/quotes/254656-one-day-your-life-will-flash-before-your-eyes-make" class="autohyperlink" title="http://www.goodreads.com/quotes/254656-one-day-your-life-will-flash-before-your-eyes-make" We&#8217;ve come a long way this year, taking the <a href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/all-in-one-event-calendar/">All-in-One Event Calendar</a> through some major feature and performance upgrades and growing our plugin downloads to nearly 270k with no sign of stopping.But don&#8217;t worry, we won&#8217;t let this award go to our heads, what we&#8217;ve achieved so far is just the beginning and we intend to make good on being &#8220;the most promising startup of 2012&#8243; (and beyond). 2012";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:54:"http://time.ly/featured-event-wordcamp-vancouver-2012/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:63:"http://time.ly/featured-event-wordcamp-vancouver-2012/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Mon, 22 Oct 2012 20:50:15 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:5:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:15:"Featured Events";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"Apple";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:7:"meet-up";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Wordcamp";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"Wordpress";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:23:"http://time.ly/?p=18556";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:335:"Last week we had the pleasure of attending our first Wordcamp here in Vancouver and it was an awesome experience. Wordcamps (for the uninitiated) are meet-ups held all over the world bringing WordPress-ers of all skill levels and interests together &#8230; <a href="http://time.ly/featured-event-wordcamp-vancouver-2012/">Continued</a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"admin";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2651:"<p><img class=" wp-image-18559 alignleft" title="wordpress_icons1" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/wordpress_icons1.jpg" alt="" width="270" height="247" />Last week we had the pleasure of attending our first<a href="http://2012.vancouver.wordcamp.org/"> Wordcamp here in Vancouver</a> and it was an awesome experience. <a href="http://central.wordcamp.org/">Wordcamps</a> (for the uninitiated) are meet-ups held all over the world bringing WordPress-ers of all skill levels and interests together for day long or multi-day events to talk about everything from code, to design, to business management, to freelance etiquette and of course the future of the wonderful WordPress publishing platform.</p>\n<p>The importance of the these events to the WordPress community cannot be overstated, in fact the rise and popularity of WordPress to become, arguably <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/jjcolao/2012/09/05/the-internets-mother-tongue/">the web&#8217;s most dominant publishing platform</a> can be largely attributed to Wordcamps and <a href="http://wordpress.meetup.com/">WordPress meet-up</a> events happening around the globe that bring people together to share ideas, solve problems and advance their overall understanding of what is possible in the WP universe.</p>\n<p>It may seem strange to think of something that is essentially a big block of programming code garnering an international cult-like following but beautiful technology attracts a crowd (witness the<a href="http://theweek.com/article/index/229766/5-signs-that-apple-is-a-cult"> kingdom of Apple</a>). With WordPress as an open-source, contributive platform this is especially the case.Wordpress is made and largely governed by it&#8217;s community of users and programmers, no single entity really controls it (although the company <a href="http://automattic.com/">Automattic</a>owns<a href="www.wordpress.com">wordpress.com</a> and manages the central code contributions to <a href="http://wordpress.org/">WordPress</a>). It is quiet possibly the web&#8217;s greatest example of a sophisticated, democratized communication platform, where the tools, the processes and the culture evolve in an open forum for all to see and participate in. It really is a beautiful thing.</p>\n<p>At Wordcamp Vancouver we caught up with one of the main organizers <a href="https://twitter.com/mor10">Morten Rand-Hendriksen</a> to talk about why Wordcamps make the WordPress world go around.</p>\n<div class="entry-content-asset"><iframe width="940" height="529" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/KU1PWcdCMBc?feature=oembed" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:59:"http://time.ly/featured-event-wordcamp-vancouver-2012/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:6;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:56:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n			\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:15:"Time Well Spent";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"http://time.ly/time-well-spent/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:40:"http://time.ly/time-well-spent/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Wed, 10 Oct 2012 23:12:21 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:6:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16:"Thoughts on Time";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Antiphon";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:11:"experiences";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"family";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"happiness";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:5;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4:"time";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:23:"http://time.ly/?p=16223";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:286:"Time well spentsuch a familiar phrase. If someone said it to you, youd know what they were getting at. But where does the expression come from and what does it really mean? The first person (that we know of) to &#8230; <a href="http://time.ly/time-well-spent/">Continued</a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Jonathan";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6296:"<p><img class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-16411" style="border: 1px solid black;" title="Fans at rock show" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/fans-at-a-concert-300x224.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="224" />Time well spentsuch a familiar phrase. If someone said it to you, youd know what they were getting at. But where does the expression come from and what does it <em>really</em> mean?</p>\n<p>The first person (that we know of) to speak of <em>spending</em> time, in the way that one might spend a currency, was Antiphon (c. 480-411 BC), and as well see in future posts we owe a lot of our thinking about time to Greek writers and philosophers of this period. We dont know too much about Antiphon, (although this Wikpedia entry gives us a good start: <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antiphon_(person">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antiphon_(person</a>)</p>\n<p>Anyway, what interests us here is not so much who Antiphon was, as what he said. The expression that concerns us is this: <em>the most costly outlay is the outlay of time</em>. Now, we normally say that the sorts of things that we can <em>spend</em> are resourcesthings like energy, money or effort. So a literal reading of this expression might suggest that time <em>is</em> a resource. But if thats right, then time is going to be very much unlike other resources.</p>\n<p>For one thing, once its gone, time <em>cannot</em> be replaced, unlike money or effort. Nor can we find a substitute as we might try to for a natural resource, like oil or coal. Quite unlike all of our other resources, we cant control the <em>rate</em> at which we use up time nor can we store it.</p>\n<p>In fact, things get stranger still! If I spend some money, or energy, then in return I get something back. If I spend my money, I get <img class="alignright  wp-image-16414" style="border: 1px solid black;" title="usr_150707215554_hour-glass" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/usr_150707215554_hour-glass.jpg" alt="" width="184" height="227" />goods; if I spend energy, I get some effect. But, if I spend my time doing something, then I dont <em>seem</em> to <em>get</em> anything. How can this be right if were going to claim that times so <em>valuable</em>? If I can spend time without getting anything, surely that makes time our <em>least</em> valuable resource!</p>\n<p>But of course, we <em>do</em> get something when we spend our time on something. We get experiences. Experiences can be valuable. In fact, experiences can be <em>incredibly </em>valuablejust think of the ones that matter most to you. So, times a resource that you cant store, that you cant replace and that you cant control. And youre spending it on experiences every waking second of every single day of your life.</p>\n<p><img class="size-medium wp-image-16413 alignleft" style="border: 1px solid black;" title="stock-footage-people-walking-jogging-fishing-at-a-park-by-the-beach-at-sunset-in-hawaii" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/stock-footage-people-walking-jogging-fishing-at-a-park-by-the-beach-at-sunset-in-hawaii-e1349910092994.jpg" alt="" width="249" height="224" /></p>\n<p>Now if time is such a valuable resource, then what <em>should</em> we do with it? Are there particular sorts of behavior that are <em>better</em> uses ofour time than others? Recent research suggests that there are. Some research suggests that long working hours are negatively correlated with emotional satisfaction in adults<a title="" href="#_ftn1">[1]</a> and other research shows that people are happier with <em>experiential</em> purchases than they are with material purchases.<a title="" href="#_ftn2">[2]</a> We also know that time spent engaged in socially connecting activities, such as spending time with family, comprise the happiest parts of the day.<a title="" href="#_ftn3">[3]</a> All of which suggests that we would do well to try to work fewer hours, concentrate our financial resources on experiential purchases and spend more time with our friends and family. Maybe thats just common sense.</p>\n<p>But if you want to feel like youve more time on your handsthat youre more <em>time affluent</em>one recent study suggests that the best thing that you can do is give it away for free.<a title="" href="#_ftn4">[4]</a> The study, led by <a href="https://marketing.wharton.upenn.edu/profile/388/">Cassie Mogilner at the University ofPennsylvania</a>, found that people who gave up their time to do things for others, found themselves with a feeling of having more time than those who were given <em>free</em> time. Just as we have the saying, you have to spend money to make money, this looks to be a case where we need to spend time to make time! Given the connections mentioned above between time affluence and happiness, it looks like it might be a sound investment.</p>\n<div>\n<hr align="left" size="1" width="33%" />\n<div>\n<p><a title="" href="#_ftnref">[1]</a> Kasser, T. and Brown, K 2003. <a href="http://www.kirkwarrenbrown.vcu.edu/wp-content/pubs/Kasser%20&amp;%20Brown%20TBYT%202004.pdf">On Time, Happiness, and Ecological Footprints</a>, in J. deGraaf (ed.), <em>Take Back your Time: Fighting Overwork and Time Poverty in America</em> (Berrett-Koehler, San Francisco, CA), 107112</p>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p><a title="" href="#_ftnref">[2]</a> Van Boven, L. and Gilovich, T. 2003, <a href="http://dtserv2.compsy.uni-jena.de/ss2012/sozpsy_uj/31119589/content.nsf/Pages/97A6BE3B19E73ABFC1257A4600452E4A/$FILE/Boven%20on%20To%20Do%20or%20to%20Have.pdf">To Do or to Have? That Is the Question</a><em>, Journal of Personality and Social Psychology</em>, 85, 11931202</p>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p><a title="" href="#_ftnref">[3]</a> Csikszentmihalyi, M and Hunter, J. 2003. <a href="http://www.mendedreality.com/private/docs/CSIKSZENTMIHALYI2003.pdf">Happiness in Everyday Life: The uses of experience sampling</a>, <em>Journal of Happiness Studies</em>, 4, 185-99</p>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p><a title="" href="#_ftnref">[4]</a> Molinger, C., Chance, Z. and Norton, D. forthcoming. <a href="https://marketing.wharton.upenn.edu/files/?whdmsaction=public:main.file&amp;fileID=3722">Giving Time Gives You Time</a>, <em>Psychological Science</em></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:36:"http://time.ly/time-well-spent/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:7;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:44:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n\n		\n		\n			\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:57:"Introducing +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:2:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4:"News";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16:"Thoughts What is Time? How do we measure it? Where does it come from? Is it outside of us or just in our heads? If a clock ticks in the forest and no one&#8217;s around, does it really tell the &#8230; <a href="http://time.ly/introducing-timelys-time-philosopher-jonathan-tallant/">Continued</a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"admin";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2571:"<p><img class=" wp-image-15471 alignleft" title="spiral-clock" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/spiral-clock-300x294.jpg" alt="" width="240" height="235" />Time. What is <em>Time</em>? How do we measure it? Where does it come from? Is it outside of us or just in our heads? If a clock ticks in the forest and no one&#8217;s around, does it really tell the time? What is a <em>good time</em>? What is a <em>bad time</em>? Getting a little too deep for you? Well you may think that a calendar software developer has no business waxing philosophical about something as nebulous as time but you&#8217;d be wrong! We&#8217;re time geeks here to the extreme. We like to look at time from all sorts of different angles, and we love talking with people who do the same, that&#8217;s why were excited to introduce a our new guest blogger, Jonathan Tallant!</p>\n<p>Jonathan is a time philosopherat the <a href="http://www.nottingham.ac.uk/index.aspx">University of<em></em>Nottingham</a>. That&#8217;s right. A <em><a href="http://www.nottingham.ac.uk/philosophy/people/jonathan.tallant">Time Philosopher</a>.</em>As far as we&#8217;re concerned that&#8217;s just<img class="alignright  wp-image-15470" title="a5oxpox2wlef9g3uspap" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/a5oxpox2wlef9g3uspap-300x225.jpeg" alt="" width="240" height="180" /> one step down from <a href="http://images.epilogue.net/users/nathie/BadGuySorcererApril72.jpg">Time Sorcerer</a> and well above your common <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JwnjENpIyq0">Time Bandit</a>. Alas Jonathan is not involved in the direct manipulation of time per say but he does posit a variety of fascinating theories and themes on how humansperceiveand experience time. As such we asked him to help us explore the concept of time experience as it relates to events, great and small. His first guest post appears next week and we&#8217;ll be hounding him for more whenever he&#8217;s got the (wait for it) &#8211; <strong><em>time!</em></strong></p>\n<p>Check out some of Jonathan&#8217;s videos on YouTube and stay tuned for next week&#8217;s post in <a href="http://time.ly/category/thoughts-on-time/">Thoughts on Time.</a></p>\n<div class="entry-content-asset"><iframe Stories: Jacksonopolis";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:46:"http://time.ly/calendar-stories-jacksonopolis/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:55:"http://time.ly/calendar-stories-jacksonopolis/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Mon, 01 Oct 2012 15:30:33 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16:"Calendar Stories";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:23:"http://time.ly/?p=14066";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:317:"One href="http://time.ly/calendar-stories-jacksonopolis/">Continued</a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"admin";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5513:"<p>One of the things we love here at Timely is coming across calendar users who really understand the potential of our All-in-One Event Calendar plugin to connect communities via cross-calendar sharing and make it easy for people to find the events they care about. That&#8217;s why starting this month we&#8217;re launching a new monthly blog series called <strong>Calendar Stories</strong>to highlight some of the best examples of our plugin being used around the world.</p>\n<p><img class="size-medium wp-image-14069 alignleft" title="jacksonopolis1" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/jacksonopolis1-300x300.jpeg" alt="" width="300" height="300" />A few weeks ago the folks over at <a href="http://www.jacksonopolis.com/" target="_blank">Jacksonopolis.com</a>Tweeted us to show off their new community calendar set-up. Jacksonopolis is setting itself up to be the go-to source for community news and events for <a href="https://maps.google.ca/maps?q=Jackson+Michigan&amp;ie=UTF-8&amp;hq=&amp;hnear=0x883d25593e337b6b:0xce45a6328e9bd551,Jackson,+MI,+USA&amp;gl=ca&amp;ei=pfhlUJPmH6TYigKh3ICwCg&amp;ved=0CMYBELYD">Jackson, Michigan</a>. Co-founder and CEO of Jacksonopolis <a href="https://www.facebook.com/davidbuchanan">David Buchanan</a> was kind enough to answer some questions about how they&#8217;ve been using Timely&#8217;s All-in-One plugin to power their events calendar and why it&#8217;s important for communities like Jackson to have a unified events platform to stay informed and connected.</p>\n<h4>Could you describe what Jacksonopolis is and how it came to be?</h4>\n<p><em>Jacksonopolis showcases people, places, culture, and community in Jackson, Michigan. We came to life because of a dire need for our community to build pride, focus creativity and grow new economic sectors. Our city has been misrepresented for some time so our team is working hard to highlight the things which make our town so great. All content is submitted by the community and the site is supported by the generous local business and organizations that continue to make it great<strong><strong>.</strong></strong></em></p>\n<h4>What prompted the need for a more networked community events calendar?</h4>\n<p><em>Weve run a new media company, Coefficient Media, since 2007 building websites and the community members came to us begging to build a well designed and usable central place for Jackson. For over 4 years we used our network to gather information and hold open meetings with the community to find their needs and wants. This is one of the reasons we love social networking; Its tools like Facebook, Twitter and web portals, which enable communication and interactivity all around us. We set our focus to foster certain interactions, how to influence and share different events with friends, family, community members and leaders to have a more organized online experience.</em><strong><strong><br />\n</strong></strong></p>\n<h4>Why is a complete events listing important for your community?</h4>\n<div id="attachment_14071" class="wp-caption alignleft" style="width: 310px"><img class="size-medium wp-image-14071 " title="Jacksonopolis2" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/Jacksonopolis2-300x300.jpeg" alt="" width="300" height="300" /><p class="wp-caption-text">A local Jackson community event.</p></div>\n<p><em>While the idea of events listings and calendars are not new to a local community, we want to take it to the next level. Technology is</em><em>changing the way we interact with our local community and we feel the need to connect more than ever. So much is happening all around us we need to calendar feature events, make them easy to share, intuitive to navigate, and able to subscribe to categories.</em></p>\n<p><em>Our goal is to tear down the existing roadblocks and let the community share and connect organically through the use of their everyday tools, like social media.<strong><strong></strong></strong></em></p>\n<h3></h3>\n<h3></h3>\n<h3></h3>\n<h3></h3>\n<h3></h3>\n<h3></h3>\n<h3></h3>\n<h4>Why did you choose Timely&#8217;s All-in-One Events Calendar for the job?</h4>\n<ol>\n<li><em>Social integration. We want the events to live in on Facebook along with being associated with our website.</em>\n<p><div id="attachment_14070" class="wp-caption alignright" style="width: 310px"><img class="size-medium wp-image-14070" title="jacksonopolis3" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/jacksonopolis3-300x223.jpeg" alt="" width="300" height="223" /><p class="wp-caption-text"><em>The Jacksonopolis team hard at work.</em></p></div></li>\n<li><em>Cross Calendar Sharing. We build a lot of calendars and the ability to link data from one to another is amazing. With Timely, the calendar we built for the Arts Council and the calendar for the Young Professionals network will have the same unified data structure!</em></li>\n</ol>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>So what&#8217;s next for Jacksonopolis? David says they&#8217;re planning on syncing filtered event data between various community calendars all using the Ai1EC to create an events network powered by individuals and businesses across their region (that&#8217;s exactly what we designed it for!). Congrats to David and his team for building a great looking site with an awesome organizational mandate. If you live, work (or travel) in the Jackson MI area, <a href="http://Jacksonopolis.com" class="autohyperlink" title="http://Jacksonopolis.com" target="_blank">Jacksonopolis.com</a> should be your first stop for news and events.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:51:"http://time.ly/calendar-stories-jacksonopolis/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:9;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:53:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n			\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:40:"Featured -- --------------------------------------------------------

--
-- Table structure for table `wp_postmeta`
--

CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS `wp_postmeta` (
  `meta_id` bigint(20) unsigned NOT NULL AUTO_INCREMENT,
  `post_id` bigint(20) unsigned NOT NULL DEFAULT '0',
  `meta_key` varchar(255) DEFAULT NULL,
  `meta_value` longtext,
  PRIMARY KEY (`meta_id`),
  KEY `post_id` (`post_id`),
  KEY `meta_key` (`meta_key`)
) ENGINE=MyISAM  DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8 AUTO_INCREMENT=3736 ;

--
-- Dumping data for table `wp_postmeta`
--

-- --------------------------------------------------------

--
-- Table structure for table `wp_posts`
--

CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS `wp_posts` (
  `ID` bigint(20) unsigned NOT NULL AUTO_INCREMENT,
  `post_author` bigint(20) unsigned NOT NULL DEFAULT '0',
  `post_date` datetime NOT NULL DEFAULT '0000-00-00 00:00:00',
  `post_date_gmt` datetime NOT NULL DEFAULT '0000-00-00 00:00:00',
  `post_content` longtext NOT NULL,
  `post_title` text NOT NULL,
  `post_excerpt` text NOT NULL,
  `post_status` varchar(20) NOT NULL DEFAULT 'publish',
  `comment_status` varchar(20) NOT NULL DEFAULT 'open',
  `ping_status` varchar(20) NOT NULL DEFAULT 'open',
  `post_password` varchar(20) NOT NULL DEFAULT '',
  `post_name` varchar(200) NOT NULL DEFAULT '',
  `to_ping` text NOT NULL,
  `pinged` text NOT NULL,
  `post_modified` datetime NOT NULL DEFAULT '0000-00-00 00:00:00',
  `post_modified_gmt` datetime NOT NULL DEFAULT '0000-00-00 00:00:00',
  `post_content_filtered` longtext NOT NULL,
  `post_parent` bigint(20) unsigned NOT NULL DEFAULT '0',
  `guid` varchar(255) NOT NULL DEFAULT '',
  `menu_order` int(11) NOT NULL DEFAULT '0',
  `post_type` varchar(20) NOT NULL DEFAULT 'post',
  `post_mime_type` varchar(100) NOT NULL DEFAULT '',
  `comment_count` bigint(20) NOT NULL DEFAULT '0',
  PRIMARY KEY (`ID`),
  KEY `post_name` (`post_name`),
  KEY `type_status_date` (`post_type`,`post_status`,`post_date`,`ID`),
  KEY `post_parent` (`post_parent`),
  KEY `post_author` (`post_author`)
) ENGINE=MyISAM  DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8 AUTO_INCREMENT=26990 ;

--
-- Dumping data for table `wp_posts`
--

-- --------------------------------------------------------

--
-- Table structure for table `wp_terms`
--

CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS `wp_terms` (
  `term_id` bigint(20) unsigned NOT NULL AUTO_INCREMENT,
  `name` varchar(200) NOT NULL DEFAULT '',
  `slug` varchar(200) NOT NULL DEFAULT '',
  `term_group` bigint(10) NOT NULL DEFAULT '0',
  PRIMARY KEY (`term_id`),
  UNIQUE KEY `slug` (`slug`),
  KEY `name` (`name`)
) ENGINE=MyISAM  DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8 AUTO_INCREMENT=42 ;

-- Dumping data for table `wp_terms`

--
-- Table structure for table `wp_term_relationships`
--

CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS `wp_term_relationships` (
  `object_id` bigint(20) unsigned NOT NULL DEFAULT '0',
  `term_taxonomy_id` bigint(20) unsigned NOT NULL DEFAULT '0',
  `term_order` int(11) NOT NULL DEFAULT '0',
  PRIMARY KEY (`object_id`,`term_taxonomy_id`),
  KEY `term_taxonomy_id` (`term_taxonomy_id`)
) ENGINE=MyISAM DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8;

--
-- Table structure for table `wp_term_taxonomy`
--

CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS `wp_term_taxonomy` (
  `term_taxonomy_id` bigint(20) unsigned NOT NULL AUTO_INCREMENT,
  `term_id` bigint(20) unsigned NOT NULL DEFAULT '0',
  `taxonomy` varchar(32) NOT NULL DEFAULT '',
  `description` longtext NOT NULL,
  `parent` bigint(20) unsigned NOT NULL DEFAULT '0',
  `count` bigint(20) NOT NULL DEFAULT '0',
  PRIMARY KEY (`term_taxonomy_id`),
  UNIQUE KEY `term_id_taxonomy` (`term_id`,`taxonomy`),
  KEY `taxonomy` (`taxonomy`)
) ENGINE=MyISAM  DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8 AUTO_INCREMENT=42 ;

-- Table structure for table `wp_usermeta`
--

CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS `wp_usermeta` (
  `umeta_id` bigint(20) unsigned NOT NULL AUTO_INCREMENT,
  `user_id` bigint(20) unsigned NOT NULL DEFAULT '0',
  `meta_key` varchar(255) DEFAULT NULL,

  KEY `user_id` (`user_id`),
  KEY `meta_key` (`meta_key`)
) ENGINE=MyISAM  DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8 AUTO_INCREMENT=73 ;

--
-- Table structure for table `wp_users`
--

CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS `wp_users` (
  `ID` bigint(20) unsigned NOT NULL AUTO_INCREMENT,
  `user_login` varchar(60) NOT NULL DEFAULT '',
  `user_pass` varchar(64) NOT NULL DEFAULT '',
  `user_nicename` varchar(50) NOT NULL DEFAULT '',
  `user_email` varchar(100) NOT NULL DEFAULT '',
  `user_url` varchar(100) NOT NULL DEFAULT '',
  `user_registered` datetime NOT NULL DEFAULT '0000-00-00 00:00:00',
  `user_activation_key` varchar(60) NOT NULL DEFAULT '',
  `user_status` int(11) NOT NULL DEFAULT '0',
  `display_name` varchar(250) NOT NULL DEFAULT '',
  PRIMARY KEY (`ID`),
  KEY `user_login_key` (`user_login`),
  KEY `user_nicename` (`user_nicename`)
) ENGINE=MyISAM  DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8 AUTO_INCREMENT=6 ;

--
-- Dumping data for table `wp_users`
--
